ctiferous sinus","Suspensory ligament","Alveolar bud","Terminal ductule","Myoepithelial junction"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eterminal ductule\u003C/strong\u003E connects each lobule to the larger ductal system of the breast. This forms part of the terminal duct lobular unit (TDLU), which is the functional unit of the breast.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elactiferous sinus\u003C/strong\u003E is a dilated portion of the main duct near the nipple that serves as a temporary milk storage area. The \u003Cstrong\u003Esuspensory ligament\u003C/strong\u003E (Cooper\u0027s ligament) provides structural support to the breast but does not participate in milk transport. An \u003Cstrong\u003Ealveolar bud\u003C/strong\u003E is part of the secretory unit within the lobule where milk is produced. A \u003Cstrong\u003Emyoepithelial junction\u003C/strong\u003E is not an anatomical structure - myoepithelial cells are contractile cells that surround the ducts and alveoli.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding breast anatomy is crucial as the terminal duct lobular unit is the site of origin for most breast cancers.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The terminal duct lobular unit (TDLU) is the functional unit of the breast, consisting of a terminal duct and its associated lobules.","Terminal ducts connect lobules to larger ducts via specialised segments called terminal ductules."],"references":["Zucca-Matthes G, Urban C, Vallejo A. Anatomy of the nipple and breast ducts. Gland Surg. 2016 Feb;5(1):32-6. doi: 10.3978/j.issn.2227-684X.2015.05.10. PMID: 26855906; PMCID: PMC4716863","Javed A, Lteif A. Development of the human breast. Semin Plast Surg. 2013 Feb;27(1):5-12. doi: 10.1055/s-0033-1343989. PMID: 24872732; PMCID: PMC3706056","Biswas SK, Banerjee S, Baker GW, Kuo CY, Chowdhury I. The Mammary Gland: Basic Structure and Molecular Signaling during Development. Int J Mol Sci. 